A surprise find for us visiting DC. The choices were very broad. We picked the grilled chicken, the wreck and the turkey club. All were very good. The ordering process is convouted though for first timers and the noise from the exhaust makes it hard to figure out what's going on.

While the food was okay, the experience and staff are lacking.  After ordering, we went to wait for our sandwiches, salads, and soups.  The staff making sandwiches were doing anything but that.  Milling around chatting.  Finally a lady asked what we were waiting for and I listed every item.  She made one sandwich and then ignored me.  She finally realized I was still standing there and asked what I was waiting for.  I told her all the items we hadn’t received yet.  She then told another lady about the chicken salad, which finally got made.  It was only then that we were directed to the cash register for the rest of our order.  Upon getting there, we were told they were out of side salads.  Very unapologetic, as if I should have known they were out back when I ordered at the first counter.  They offered soup in exchange — no, I ordered a side salad and my child did want soup.  I would have ordered a larger salad for him if I knew they were out.  Magically a side salad appeared... so I guess they were not really out?!  Cashier was rude and acted like we were annoying him by asking for the soup and Mac and cheese we’d ordered at the first counter.  We don’t frequent Potbelly often, so I hope this lack of service is not indicative of the whole chain.  Suffice to say, I won’t be coming back to this location on future trips to DC.

I have only been to this Potbelly's location three times in the last two months. I get the same thing every single time. The Urban salad with no onions and no bleu cheese. Simple. All three times they have failed to get it right. I understand if it is busy, so I just pick out the onions and cheese as best I can. Today it was not busy. I was the ONLY person getting a salad. You guessed it...onion on it. At least they held the bleu cheese. The funniest part is the girl even said, "Urban with no onions or bleu cheese, as she handed it to me. I should not have assumed she got it right and checked anyway. I hate having to pick through a salad to take out the onions. Meetings today do not leave me enough time to do this and have time to eat the salad. It is not difficult. Also not difficult: finding a new place to get my salad.
